Nobody drifts toward a better marriage. Drift only goes one direction — toward polite roommates, parallel lives, conversations that never get past logistics. Maybe that's where you are. Or maybe it's louder than that: the same fight on repeat, a separation you didn't want, trust that got broken and doesn't know how to heal, or teenagers who treat you like furniture.

Men usually wait a long time to deal with this. The average man shows up when the pain of staying the same finally beats the awkwardness of asking for help.

## What's actually going on

(Edit)- Black phone

Most relationship patterns run on old programming. How you fight, how you shut down, what you do with disappointment, how you handle being disrespected — most of that was installed long before you met her, usually in the house you grew up in. Under pressure, we don't do what we intend. We do what we know.

That's not an excuse; it's a starting point. A man can't change a pattern he's never actually looked at.

## How counseling helps

(R.C. Sproul-mirror)

This is individual counseling — the work is on your side of the street. We'll get honest about the patterns you bring into the relationship: where they came from, what triggers them, and what they're costing. We'll work on the skills most men were never taught — saying what's actually going on inside instead of making people guess, staying present in conflict instead of blowing up or checking out, rebuilding trust in actions rather than promises.

And we'll anchor it in something sturdier than technique. Scripture's picture of a husband and father is neither a doormat nor a dictator — it's a man strong enough to go first: first to apologize, first to listen, first to change. That kind of leadership can restart things you thought were finished.

## When to reach out

If you can feel the distance and you're still telling yourself it'll sort itself out — it won't. Drift doesn't self-correct. The men who save their marriages are usually just the ones who moved before it was an emergency.
